# Day 5 – Docker Networking (Hands-On)

## Objective
Understand Docker port mapping and container networking through practical testing.

## What I Practiced

- Ran Nginx container in detached mode
- Exposed container port using `-p HOST:CONTAINER`
- Tested service using curl
- Ran multiple containers with different host ports
- Observed container lifecycle behavior
- Used docker inspect and docker network commands

## Commands Used

sudo docker run -d -p 8081:80 --name nginx1 nginx
sudo docker run -d -p 8082:80 --name nginx2 nginx
sudo docker ps
curl localhost:8081
curl localhost:8082
sudo docker stop nginx1
sudo docker start nginx1
sudo docker network ls

## Key Learnings

- Containers are isolated and can use the same internal port.
- Host ports must be unique.
- Port mapping works only when container is running.
- `docker run` creates a new container.
- `docker start` restarts an existing container.
- Docker uses bridge network by default.

✅ Successfully implemented Docker networking on Raspberry Pi Linux.
